title: 3 Wheel X Carriage (2020) for FLSUN Prusa i3 (2017)

description.text:
Update (20/01/2018)

  • Added: Reinforced Carriage / Cable Strain Relief

I suggest printing the carriage at a hight infill rate +30% (I did mine with 50%).

Hardware needed:

  • 2x M3x8mm
  • 5x M3x12mm
  • 2x M3x12mm (self tapping screws for "hotend mount to carriage")
  • 4x M3x20mm

  • 5x M3 hex nut

  • 2x M4x20mm

  • 2x M4 square nut

  • M5 hardware salvaged from stock carriage (flsun i3 2017)

  • Magnets 8x 6x3mm disc magnets (cooling fan assembly/inductive sensor mount)

The hotend mount is designed for a V6 clone heatsink.

123D Design file is included in the list. So feel free to edit, comment and share makes if you decide to print this carriage.

Inspired by Cbmx's Tevo Tarantula X-Rail 3 wheels system: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2497936
X-Limit Switch: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2521758
Cooling Duct: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1887970

Problems with the stock carriage:

The standard X carriage on my FLSUN i3 did not travel evenly on the extrusion. On certain points it would raise/lower the entire carriage ever so slightly.

The results are uneven lines along the X axis, especially on large rectangular parts. During operation this behavior is only visible under very close observation. An easy way to determine wether your X carriage suffers from this issue is auto-bed-leveling. The probing results will show a wave pattern along the X axis while the values along the Y axis roughly stay the same on the mesh.

For example*:
0 1 2 3
0 -0.1 +0.2 -0.2 +0.3
1 -0.1 +0.2 -0.2 +0.3
2 -0.1 +0.2 -0.2 +0.3
3 -0.1 +0.2 -0.2 +0.3

*These are fictional values to visualize the problem.

Belt Locks

Standard GT2 belt lock by alex_des: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1719926

White PU Steel Core belt lock: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2522231

I advise against using PU steel core timing belts (as seen on the picture). I never could get rid of the vibrations caused on higher speeds. Gone back to fiberglass belts and all is well.

description.text:

I decided to make my own dial indicator mount because the ones i found on here the shaft hole was too big or too small for my ebay dial indicator. If your using a stock fan you should be able to use this mount and your fan at the same time :)

PLAY

My daughter likes horses a lot, having whole herd of the model ones. So I created a set of horse jumps for her.  
Scale is (very roughly) 1:20, fitting the common horse figures.

There are two variants, files for the simple one starting with A_ and for the more complex one with B_. Variant A
To make one set of jumps, print 2x both of A_base.stl and A_post.stl. Put the notch in post to square hole in the cross base. You may want to print additional cross bases, because they may be used as separate risers for the cavalletti as a small jump. Variant B
To make one set of jumps, print 2x each of B_base.stl, B_top.stl, B_post_1.stl and B_post_2.stl. This makes the square frame. To fill in the frame, the easy way is to print 2x B_side_full.stl and insert it to slit in the top and bottom part. The slightly harder way is to print 4x B_side_half.stl and put them back to back to create a crosshatch. Crossbars
I didn't print the crossbars, because they're supposed to be round in shape and thus are hard to print. I used sticks of hot glue instead and instead of painting them, I used colored sticky tape to make the strips. Additional tips
You may use hot glue or superglue to put the parts together permanently, but they should hold just fine without it. For added realism, you can print stickers with logos and stick them to square areas of side parts. Print mix of various types and combination. In real show jumping courses there are 7-16 jumps.

description.text:
First World Problem #473: Empty Filament Spools

Turn you empty spools into giant spinning tops! These easy-to-print inserts are sized for the 53.5mm dia holes in eSun/Inland spools, but you can re-scale them anywhere from 75% to 125% to fit your particular spool.

I've posted 3 different style tops. The spiral give an interesting visual effect when it spins, but it provides the least gription when you go to spin it up.

Watch them go: https://youtu.be/Cjf1cexgRSk

Printer:

UDIO

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

These are sized for 53.5mm dia holes. Accurately measure the diameter of the holes in your spool and scale up or down accordingly. In your slicer, you should be able to scale in just X and Y, leaving the Z scale at 100%. I'd suggest printing just the first few millimeters of the spool top tip to check the fit before printing the whole thing. (If you don't get a really tight fit, you can always use a few drops of superglue to hold the inserts in place.)

Make sure to print this pretty hot and slow. The walls are thing for quick printing but they should plenty sturdy if your layers are fully fused.

Getting your tops spun up takes a little finesse. Spin the stem between your sliding palms as shown in the video. The trick is to contact and release the stem with both palms at exactly the same time. Once you've got the top spinning, you can continue to recharge it with your palms as it slows down.

Created a remote display for a Photon based sprinkler system that fits in a standard 4X4 electrical box. This display has a small pin hole (lower center) for a reset button and two areas (left and right of the .96" display) to hold touch sensors. Simple and clean from the front point of view.

This display inserts into a Legrand 2 gang cover (# AWP2GWWH4) from Lowes. A slight modification is needed on the Legrand mounting plate for it to work. The Legrand mounting plate is made to hold 2 accessories, (i.e. Switches, Outlets, dimmers, etc.) so there are two metal separators which needs to be bend 90 degrees out of the way (into the box). With that modification, the display easily sets between the mounting and cover plates. Also I don't use the 4 plastic spacers included with the plate mount.

I printed the display using PLA white which matches the color of the cover plate fairly well at 10% fill and .2 mm layer height. I used small screws to hold the assembles together. All electronics are held in place with the LCD support, Photon support, and the Touch mounts. I used wire-wrap to electrically connect it all together. The touch sensors I used have a red power LED. I used black finger nail polish the black it out.

Special Print Setting

To get a clean and flat gloss front, I printed on a glass plate, front down. The Printer must be set to ...
Support "Yes"
Raft "No"

I found how to do this on the internet.
I used 123D. I still have not upgraded.

This was a remix I did on helicopterguru's setup.

First I cleared the area where the adjustment knob goes.

I added the second endstop mount, and routing for the wiring, as well as added permanent JST connectors. (All of my wiring is design to unplug and mount different extruder setups)

I also modded the touch sensor mount as I do not have a sensor at the moment. I made it a cable guide instead.

The cable guide on the top could be better, if I reprint this part I will design is with a slightly taller tower to ensure my cables don't droop and get in the way during movement. I also use a rubber band around it to keep the cables from wiggling during print. (considering a clamping design of sorts)

For the ducting I also added some internal chamfers to improve printing without supports.

(Printed in ABS which always comes out a bit sloppy for me compared to PLA)

I created this simple little vent for the purpose of keeping the dust out of my CNC machine's control box. It uses standard pantyhose for it's filter element. 6mm Studding by 120mm long.
6mm wingnut or thumb nut.
3 x 6mm half nuts

One used in the insert.

description.text:
OpenTUSH

Yet another remix of the TUSH filament spool holder.

I created this mostly because I wanted to work out how to do those nice curves in OpenSCAD. Then I discovered TUSH++ and liked the idea of the jointing plate so I created one of those in the this design file too. The two parts need to be together as the thickness of the side plates dictates the slot width of the jointing plate.

I also added an M3 hole so that the side plates can be screwed together if your bearing spindles are not a "snug" enough fit. With my printer I find some are and some aren't within the same print! The screws also mean these can be used without the jointing plate, just like the original TUSH.

The design is fully parametrised meaning you can change dimensions in the variables at the top of the file in the OpenSCAD editor to suit whatever bearing you might have or spool diameter you want to support. If you want to make the Jointing plates longer or shorter, you just change the number of slots you want. Details in the OpenSCAD design file comments.

Thanks to all those who have gone before for giving me the inspiration to make this thing. If it is useful, or you find bugs or ways to improve it further please feel free to remix and give me a shout back.

description.text:
How to build grip for Canon 400D.

Required hardware (see PIC001.JPG):

  • Glue (CA or Epoxy);
  • A couple of rechargeable batteries 18650;
  • Container for the batteries;
  • Any died AA or AAA battery to make contacts;
  • Male and female connectors;
  • Nail (1/10" or 2,5 mm diameter). It should fit to small hole in the bottom of the camera body;
  • 1/4" screw. If you cannot bye inch thread screw, you can get it from cheap selfie stick.

Steps to build:
1) Print the parts (see PIC002.JPG).
2) Use sandpaper to fit Part 1 and Part 2.
3) Saw off screw and nail (PIC003.JPG). Glue them with Part 3 and Part 4 (PIC004.JPG). Let the glue dry.
4) Remove the battery box cap from the camera body (PIC005.JPG).
5) Fasten Part 1 to body, put Part 4 with nail to the small hole. Align Part 1 along to body
and glue Part 4 by a couple of glue drops (PIC006.JPG).
6) Unfasten Part 1. Put Part 5 into battery cap place (PIC007.JPG), put a couple of glue drops on it.
Fasten Part 1 again. Let glue dry.
7) Unfasten Part 1. Glue Part 4 and Part 5 from the bottom side (PIC008.JPG). Grip is ready.
8) Make a couple of contacts from died AA or AAA battery body and solder them to female connector.
Contacts width is 4 mm (PIC009.JPG).
9) Glue contacts to Part 6. Double check a polarity. Red is plus, black is minus. Glue Part 7 to Part 6.
The battery stub is ready (PIC010.JPG).
10) Solder male connector to battery container. Load two charged batteries 18650 into container (PIC011.JPG).
Double check a polarity. Red is plus, black is minus.
11) Connect the container and the battery stub. Double check a polarity. Multimetr has to show about 8 Volts
and polarity has to be correct (PIC012.JPG). Disconnect the container and the battery stub.
12) Assembly the grip. Set the battery stub into the body (PIC013.JPG). Fasten the grip (PIC014.JPG).
Load the container with batteries and connect it with the battery stub.
13) Since we checked the polarity six times, the power can be turned on - PIC015.JPG.
The camera has to work. Ta-dam-m-m!!! Close the grip cap.

Note: If the grip cap moves too easy, put a small peace of foam under the battery container.

.

The main parts should assemble using 6mm or 1/4 inch bolts.

Printing in PLA or ABS etc should be fine.
The base part should be printed in the supplied orientation, with supports.
No supports required for anything else. Raft or brim not required unless you really need them.
The wheels can have a thin rubber tyre (tire) added to them after printing, by simply wrapping a layer or two of self amalgamating tape around them, but don't wrap the tape over the sides or the wheels won't fit or may bind.
